B.Ph=new A.aE("e_internal_1","internals","Widget-Element-RenderObject",B.bH,B.A,"How does Flutter's reconciliation algorithm work? How does it decide to update vs recreate elements?","Flutter walks the widget tree top-down comparing new widgets with existing elements using Widget.canUpdate() \u2014 which checks runtimeType and key. If canUpdate returns true, the element is updated with the new widget config. If false, the old element is deactivated and a new one is created.","static bool canUpdate(Widget oldWidget, Widget newWidget) {\n  return oldWidget.runtimeType == newWidget.runtimeType && oldWidget.key == newWidget.key;\n}\n\nThis is why:\n- Changing widget type at a position causes full subtree rebuild\n- Keys allow preservation when widgets move in a list\n- const widgets always canUpdate (same instance)\n\nThe algorithm is O(n) \u2014 it's a linear walk, not a diff. Flutter avoids the O(n\xb3) tree diff problem by making it the developer's responsibility to use keys correctly.",null,null)
B.Pz=new A.aE("e_internal_2","internals","Rendering Pipeline",B.bH,B.A,"Explain how repaint boundaries work internally. When should you add them?","RepaintBoundary creates a separate compositing Layer for its subtree. When a child needs repainting, only its layer is repainted \u2014 parent and sibling layers are untouched. Add them around: frequently animating widgets, complex CustomPaint, scrollable item content.","Without RepaintBoundary: a small change repaints the entire layer (potentially the full screen).\nWith RepaintBoundary: the subtree gets its own OffsetLayer. Only that layer's content is re-rasterized.\n\nDevTools Paint indicator shows repaint regions. Green flashes = area being repainted. If you see the full screen flashing, add RepaintBoundary.\n\nOverusing RepaintBoundary wastes GPU memory (each layer is a texture). Profile before adding.",null,null)
B.Pa=new A.aE("e_internal_3","internals","Engine",B.bH,B.A,"How does Flutter communicate with the underlying platform (iOS/Android)?","The Flutter engine (C++) hosts the Dart VM and provides: platform channels (binary messaging), a rendering surface (Metal/Vulkan/OpenGL), text layout (libtxt), networking (via platform), and plugin registration. The engine embeds in a platform-specific shell (FlutterViewController on iOS, FlutterActivity on Android).","Architecture layers:\n1. Framework (Dart) \u2014 widgets, rendering, gestures\n2. Engine (C++) \u2014 Dart VM, Skia/Impeller, text, platform channels\n3. Embedder (platform-specific) \u2014 window, input, lifecycle\n\nPlatform channels use binary serialization (StandardMethodCodec). Messages pass through the engine's binary messenger between Dart and the platform thread. This is asynchronous by design.",null,null)
B.Pv=new A.aE("e_internal_4","internals","Compilation",B.bH,B.A,"Explain Flutter's compilation modes: JIT, AOT, and kernel snapshots.","Debug mode uses JIT (Just-In-Time) \u2014 compiles Dart to kernel bytecode, enables hot reload via incremental compilation. Release mode uses AOT (Ahead-Of-Time) \u2014 compiles to native ARM/x86 code for maximum performance. Profile mode is AOT with debugging symbols.","JIT (debug):\n- Dart VM interprets kernel bytecode\n- Hot reload: diff \u2192 kernel \u2192 update VM classes\n- Slower, larger binary, full debugging\n\nAOT (release):\n- dart2native compiles to machine code\n- No VM overhead, tree shaking removes dead code\n- Smaller binary, faster startup, no hot reload\n\nKernel snapshot: intermediate representation used by JIT. The analyzer transforms Dart \u2192 kernel \u2192 VM loads it.",null,null)
B.PH=new A.aE("e_perf_1","performance","Memory",B.bH,B.A,"How does Dart's garbage collector work? What are the implications for Flutter performance?","Dart uses a generational, semi-space GC. Young generation: fast bump-pointer allocation, frequent minor GC (stop-the-world, <1ms). Old generation: mark-sweep-compact, infrequent, can cause jank. Implications: avoid promoting objects to old gen unnecessarily; const and immutable objects reduce GC pressure.","Young space: new objects allocated here. Minor GC copies live objects to the other semi-space. Dead objects are left behind (zero cost).\nOld space: objects that survive multiple minor GCs. Major GC is more expensive.\n\nFor Flutter:\n- Short-lived objects (widgets rebuilt each frame) stay in young gen \u2192 cheap GC\n- Leaking objects (forgotten listeners, unclosed streams) promote to old gen \u2192 expensive GC \u2192 potential jank\n- Use const constructors to allocate once, not per-frame",null,null)
B.Pf=new A.aE("e_perf_2","performance","Optimization",B.bH,B.A,"Your app has consistent jank (dropped frames) during scrolling. Walk through your debugging process.","1) Run in profile mode. 2) Open DevTools Performance tab, record scroll. 3) Identify if jank is in build, layout, paint, or rasterize phase. 4) If build: check Widget Inspector for excessive rebuilds, add const/extract widgets. 5) If paint: add RepaintBoundary, check for saveLayer/clipPath abuse. 6) If rasterize: reduce opacity layers, simplify shaders. 7) Check for work on main isolate that should be in compute().","Common scroll jank causes:\n- Building complex widgets on-demand without caching (ListView.builder helps)\n- Images decoding on main thread (use cacheWidth/cacheHeight)\n- Opacity widget creating saveLayer (use FadeTransition instead)\n- ClipRRect with complex clips (use clipBehavior: Clip.hardEdge)\n- Expensive computations in build (move to isolate)\n- Too many layers (merge small layers)",null,null)
B.C_=new A.A9(2,"scenario")
B.Py=new A.aE("e_arch_1","architecture","SOLID",B.bH,B.C_,"You're building a feature that needs to fetch data from an API, cache it locally, sync changes, and handle offline mode. Design the architecture.","Use a Repository with dual data sources (RemoteDataSource + LocalDataSource). The Repository decides which source to use based on connectivity. A SyncService handles background sync. Use sealed classes for data states (Fresh, Cached, Stale, Error). The UI layer observes Streams from the Repository for real-time updates.","Repository pattern with offline-first:\n1. Read: try local cache \u2192 if stale, fetch remote \u2192 update cache \u2192 emit\n2. Write: save locally \u2192 queue for sync \u2192 sync when online\n3. Conflict resolution: last-write-wins or merge strategy\n\nclass UserRepository {\n  Stream<DataState<User>> watchUser(String id) {\n    // emit cached data immediately\n    // fetch fresh data in background\n    // emit fresh data when available\n  }\n}",null,null)
B.PK=new A.aE("e_arch_2","architecture","Clean Architecture",B.bH,B.A,"How do you handle cross-cutting concerns (logging, analytics, error reporting) without polluting business logic?","Use middleware/interceptors: BLoC Observers for state management events, Dio interceptors for network calls, Navigator observers for screen tracking. For DI: create wrapper services that delegate to the real service + side-effect (logging). Aspect-Oriented approach via Dart annotations + code generation.","BlocObserver: override onChange, onEvent, onError for global state logging\nDio interceptors: log requests/responses, add auth headers, handle errors\nNavigatorObserver: track screen views for analytics\nErrorBoundary widget: catch and report rendering errors\n\nThe key principle: business logic should not know about analytics/logging. These concerns are injected via middleware at the infrastructure layer.",null,null)
B.P1=new A.aE("e_platform_1","platform_integration","FFI",B.bH,B.A,"How does Dart FFI work? When would you use it over platform channels?","Dart FFI provides direct, synchronous calls to C libraries. It's faster than platform channels (no async message passing overhead). Use FFI for: high-frequency calls, performance-critical code (crypto, image processing), existing C/C++/Rust libraries. Use platform channels for: platform APIs (camera, GPS), UI-related operations, simple integrations.",'FFI is synchronous and runs in the same thread \u2014 no serialization overhead.\nfinal dylib = DynamicLibrary.open("libcrypto.so");\nfinal hash = dylib.lookupFunction<NativeHash, DartHash>("sha256");\nfinal result = hash(data); // direct C call\n\nUse ffigen to auto-generate Dart bindings from C headers.\nFor Rust: use flutter_rust_bridge for safe FFI.',null,null)
B.PN=new A.aE("e_platform_2","platform_integration","Pigeon",B.bH,B.A,"What is Pigeon and how does it improve platform channel communication?","Pigeon is a code-generation tool that creates type-safe platform channel bindings. You define APIs in Dart, and Pigeon generates the Dart, Kotlin/Java, and Swift/ObjC code. This eliminates string-based method names, manual serialization, and type mismatches.","@HostApi()\nabstract class BatteryApi {\n  int getBatteryLevel();\n}\n\nPigeon generates:\n- Dart: BatteryApi class with type-safe methods\n- Kotlin: BatteryApi interface to implement\n- The serialization/deserialization code\n\nBenefits: compile-time safety, no magic strings, auto-generated boilerplate, consistent API across platforms.",null,null)
B.PE=new A.aE("e_dart_1","dart_fundamentals","OOP",B.bH,B.A,"Explain Dart's type system: covariance, contravariance, and soundness.","Dart's type system is sound \u2014 if the static type says String, it will always be a String at runtime. Generics are covariant by default (List<Cat> is a subtype of List<Animal>), which is technically unsound but pragmatic. Dart adds runtime checks to catch violations.","Covariance: List<Cat> can be assigned to List<Animal> \u2713\nBut: List<Animal> animals = cats; animals.add(Dog()); // compiles but throws at runtime\n\nDart chose pragmatic covariance over Java-style wildcards (? extends T). The runtime check catches violations. This is a deliberate trade-off of safety for usability.\n\nFunction parameters are checked differently: parameter types are covariant in practice, return types are covariant.",null,null)
B.P9=new A.aE("e_dart_2","dart_fundamentals","Async/Await",B.bH,B.A,"How do Zones work in Dart? What are they used for?","Zones are execution contexts that intercept and modify the behavior of asynchronous operations. They can catch uncaught errors, override print, track async operations, and provide zone-local values. runZonedGuarded is used for global error handling in Flutter.","runZonedGuarded(() {\n  runApp(MyApp());\n}, (error, stack) {\n  // catches ALL uncaught async errors\n  crashReporter.report(error, stack);\n});\n\nZones intercept:\n- Timer creation (scheduleMicrotask, Timer)\n- Error handling (uncaught async errors)\n- print() calls\n- Zone-local values (like thread-local storage)\n\nFlutterError.onError handles framework errors; Zones handle Dart async errors.",null,null)
B.OR=new A.aE("e_dart_3","dart_fundamentals","OOP",B.bH,B.A,"What are extension types in Dart 3 and how do they differ from extension methods?","Extension types create a zero-cost wrapper around an existing type with a different interface. Unlike extension methods (which add methods to a type), extension types create a completely new type that compiles away to the underlying type \u2014 no runtime overhead, no allocation.",'extension type UserId(String id) {\n  bool get isValid => id.length > 0;\n}\nUserId uid = UserId("abc");\n// uid is a String at runtime, but the compiler treats it as UserId\n// Can\'t accidentally pass a raw String where UserId is expected\n\nUse cases: typed wrappers for IDs, validated types, FFI interop types, restricting APIs of existing types.',null,null)
B.RN=s([B.Ph,B.Pz,B.Pa,B.Pv,B.PH,B.Pf,B.Py,B.PK,B.P1,B.PN,B.PE,B.P9,B.OR],t.k9)
